There are many ways to do it, you just need to pick a convention. For example, one convention is that you use &quot;#&quot; as key for element name, &quot;.&quot; as key for element children, and attribute name as keys for the attributes. Following those conventions, you can produce:<p><pre><code>    {
        &quot;#&quot; = &quot;foo&quot;,
        &quot;bar&quot; = &quot;baz&quot;,
        &quot;.&quot; = [
            { &quot;#&quot; = &quot;bork&quot;, &quot;.&quot; = &quot;foo1&quot; },
            { &quot;#&quot; = &quot;bork&quot;, &quot;.&quot; = &quot;foo2&quot; }
        ]
    }
</code></pre>
Or, for something more verbose (but maybe more intelligible), you could use &quot;$element&quot; as key for element names, and &quot;$children&quot; as key for child elements / text. (The point of choosing $ as a prefix, is it is not a valid character in attribute names, so cannot conflict with them.)
